   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1190.xml"/>the Rev. Thomas
               Jones</persName><note place="foot" n="1">The transcription does not identify the
               recipient; Telford titles &apos;To Mr. Jones&apos;. <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers1190.xml"/>Rev. Thomas Jones</persName> had recently
               initiated contact with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
               (see his letter of <date when="1759-03-21">Mar. 21, 1759</date>), and would be a
               fitting person for <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> to
               ask for input on revising <hi rend="italic">NT Notes</hi>.</note></head>
         <opener><placeName>London</placeName><lb/><date when="1759-08-22">August 22, 1759</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Sir,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p><pb n="172"/>Nothing is more certain than that the kingdom of God is not <index
               indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="Mark3:25">divided against itself</term>
            </index>;<note place="foot" n="2">See <index indexName="biblical">
                  <term cRef="Mark3:25">Mark 3:25</term>
               </index>.</note> that peace and joy in the Holy Ghost are no ways obstructive of
            righteousness, even in the highest degree of it. Hold fast, therefore, that <index
               indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="Phil3:16">whereunto you have attained</term>
            </index>,<note place="foot" n="3">See <index indexName="biblical">
                  <term cRef="Phil3:16">Phil. 3:16</term>
               </index>.</note> and in peace and joy wait for perfect love. We know &apos;<index
               indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="Eph2:9">this is not of works, lest any man should boast</term>
            </index>&apos;,<note place="foot" n="4"><index indexName="biblical">
                  <term cRef="Eph2:9">Eph. 2:9</term>
               </index>.</note> and it is no more of <hi rend="italic">sufferings</hi> than it is of
            works. Nothing is absolutely pre-required but a sense of our want; and this may be a
            calm, peaceful, yea, a joyful sense of it. When I was lately in
               <placeName>Rotherham</placeName>, I talked with eleven persons who seem to be
            perfected in love.<note place="foot" n="5">See <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>,
                  <date when="1759-08-02">Aug. 2, 1759</date>, 21:221 in this edn.</note> Of these
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0857.xml"/>Jane Green</persName> (the wife of
            one of our preachers<note place="foot" n="6">Apparently a local preacher, as there were
               no itinerants of that name at the time.</note>) was <foreign rend="italic">facile
               princeps</foreign><note place="foot" n="7">&apos;Easily the
            leader&apos;.</note>—higher and deeper in experience than them all—and she never was in
            darkness or heaviness one hour during the second conviction. Only she felt in a manner
            not to be expressed her own foolishness, emptiness, and nothingness. And in this state
            she quietly continued till God said, &apos;<index indexName="biblical">
               <term cRef="Matt8:3">Be thou clean</term>
            </index>&apos;.<note place="foot" n="8">See <index indexName="biblical">
                  <term cRef="Matt8:3">Matt. 8:3</term>
               </index> and parallels.</note></p>
         <p>While I was riding (since Christmas) three- or four-and-twenty hundred miles I found no
            want of strength. But when my work was at an end, so was my strength. When I want it, I
            shall have it again. I <pb n="173"/>thought you was to have been here in
               <date>October</date>, but God&apos;s time is the best! He doth all things well. Why
            should we not trust him in all!</p>
         <closer>I am, dear sir,<lb/>
            <signed>Ever yours,<lb/><persName>John Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
         <postscript>
            <p>Will you take the time and pains to read the <hi rend="italic">Notes</hi> critically
               over, and give me your alterations and additions before I print another edition!<note
                  place="foot" n="9"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> spent <date
                     when="1759-12">December</date> revising <hi rend="italic">NT Notes</hi>,
                  resulting in its definitive 3rd edn.; see <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Journal</hi>, <date when="1759-12-12">Dec. 12, 1759</date>, 21:236 in this
                  edn.</note></p>
         </postscript>
      </body>
   </text>
